<p class="body">Kona coffee occupies a category of its own in American specialty coffee. It is the only US-grown coffee with a defined origin designation, a state-regulated grading system, and a heritage of quality production stretching back more than a century. It is also one of the most counterfeited and mislabeled food products in the country, which means buying it well requires a bit of knowledge. This guide covers everything you need.</p>

<h2 class="section-head">What Makes Kona <em>Different</em></h2>

<p class="body">Kona coffee grows in a narrow strip of land on the western slope of Hawaii's Big Island, roughly two miles wide and thirty miles long, from the towns of Kailua-Kona in the north to Honaunau in the south. This strip is defined by the slopes of two volcanoes: Hualalai and Mauna Loa. The elevation ranges from roughly 800 to 2,500 feet above sea level, which is lower than most high-quality arabica-growing regions globally. What compensates for the lower altitude is the microclimate.</p>

<p class="body">The Kona coffee belt experiences a remarkably consistent weather pattern: sunny mornings give way to clouds in the early afternoon, which produce light, regular rainfall and shade the coffee trees during the hottest part of the day. Temperatures stay mild year-round, typically in the 65 to 85 degree Fahrenheit range, with cool nights that slow cherry development and allow sugars to accumulate in the fruit. The volcanic soil, derived from Mauna Loa and Hualalai lava flows, is mineral-rich, porous, and well-draining, with natural acidity that suits coffee chemistry.</p>

<p class="body">The combination of these factors, when paired with 100% hand-picking (the steep terrain makes mechanical harvesting impossible) and the century of growing knowledge embedded in Kona's farm families, produces a coffee with a specific and recognizable profile: medium body, mild and balanced acidity, sweetness that skews toward milk chocolate and hazelnut, and a clean finish that does not linger with the bitterness or dryness common in dark-roasted commodity coffee.</p>

<h2 class="section-head">The Official Kona <em>Grading System</em></h2>

<p class="body">Hawaii state law defines a grading system for Kona coffee based primarily on bean screen size (a measure of bean diameter) and defect count per 300-gram sample. The grades, from highest to lowest, are as follows.</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">Extra Fancy</h3>
<p class="body">The highest grade available for Kona coffee. Defined by a minimum screen size of 19 (approximately 7.5mm bean diameter) and a maximum of 10 allowable defects per 300-gram sample. Extra Fancy is the largest, most uniform beans the farm produces, and the strictest defect tolerance means only the best-sorted lots qualify. Koa Coffee's Private Reserve is their Extra Fancy designation.</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">Fancy</h3>
<p class="body">One step below Extra Fancy. Minimum screen size 18, maximum 15 defects per 300 grams. Fancy lots are still excellent coffee with a clearly defined origin character. The difference between Extra Fancy and Fancy is primarily visual uniformity rather than a dramatic cup quality gap, though Extra Fancy's tighter size allows for more even roasting.</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">No. 1</h3>
<p class="body">Minimum screen size 16, maximum 20 defects. No. 1 represents the broad middle tier of Kona production, where most of a farm's yield lands. Cup quality varies more at this grade level depending on the farm's picking and processing standards. A strong No. 1 lot from a quality-focused farm can cup comparably to a Fancy from a less-rigorous operation.</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">Select</h3>
<p class="body">Minimum screen size 14, blended sizes acceptable, maximum 25 defects. Select is the grade below No. 1, where bean size is mixed and defect tolerance is higher. Still technically Hawaii-graded Kona, but below the quality tier most specialty buyers seek.</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">Prime</h3>
<p class="body">The lowest grade of certified Kona. No screen size minimum, maximum 35 defects. Prime coffee is legal Kona but unlikely to satisfy a buyer seeking the origin's best characteristics. More commonly seen in blends or bulk institutional applications.</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">Peaberry</h3>
<p class="body">Peaberry is classified separately from the screen-size grades because it is a distinct physical type rather than a quality tier. A Peaberry bean forms when only one ovule develops inside the coffee cherry, producing a single round bean rather than two flat-sided halves. Because Peaberry beans are round and tend to be denser, they roast differently and often more evenly than flat beans. They are hand-sorted at the farm and represent only about 5% of any harvest. Koa Coffee's Peaberry is their signature product.</p>

