<h2 class="section-head">100% Kona vs Kona Blends: <em>The Labeling Trap</em></h2>

<p class="body">This is the most important practical section of this guide, because the Kona coffee market has a specific, well-documented consumer deception problem built into its legal framework.</p>

<p class="body">Hawaii law allows a product to be labeled "Kona Blend" if it contains as little as 10% actual Kona coffee. The remaining 90% can be any coffee from anywhere in the world, including commodity robusta or low-grade arabica sourced from countries with far lower production costs than Hawaii. A 10% Kona blend sold at a price point that approaches genuine 100% Kona is charging for an origin story it has barely earned.</p>

<p class="body">The deception is amplified by packaging. Kona blend bags often use Hawaiian imagery, volcano photographs, hula imagery, and marketing language that implies Hawaiian authenticity. The words "Kona blend" may be in small print, while the larger design elements suggest the full Kona experience. Consumer lawsuits against blenders have resulted in settlements and label changes, but the practice continues because the margin incentive is significant.</p>

<p class="body">How to avoid it: Look for "100% Kona Coffee" on the label. Nothing less. "Kona Blend," "Kona Style," "Kona Flavored," and even "Estate Kona" without the 100% qualifier are either blend products or marketing language that does not guarantee what it implies. Buy directly from Hawaii-based farms or trusted specialty retailers with verified supply chains. The price tells you most of what you need to know: real 100% Kona cannot be sold for $12 a bag and still pay the growers fairly. If the price seems too good for Kona, it is not really Kona.</p>

<div class="callout">
  <p>A legitimate bag of 100% Kona from a quality producer costs between $40 and $120 or more, depending on grade and size. This reflects the actual cost of growing and harvesting by hand in Hawaii, where labor and land costs are among the highest in US agriculture. Any price significantly below this range should prompt the question of what is actually in the bag.</p>
</div>

