<h2 class="section-head">Peaberry: The 5% <em>That Gets the Most Attention</em></h2>

<p class="body">Every variety of coffee, in every country in the world, produces peaberry beans. The mutation that causes a single round seed to develop instead of two flat halves happens in roughly 5% of cherries across most growing regions. What distinguishes Kona Peaberry is not the mutation itself but what Koa Coffee has done with it: isolated it, hand-sorted it at the farm level, and roasted it as a dedicated product that showcases what the round bean does differently.</p>

<p class="body">The roasting argument for Peaberry is density. Two flat-sided halves have an exposed flat face that sits against the drum differently than a round bean. The round bean, moving freely in the drum with no flat surface, theoretically develops more evenly because heat reaches all surfaces consistently. Whether this produces a perceptibly different cup depends on the individual taster, but Koa's Peaberry consistently cups with what most tasters describe as slightly more clarity and brightness than the flat-bean grades from the same farm.</p>

<p class="body">The story argument for Peaberry is scarcity. Five percent of a harvest is genuinely rare in a way that "Extra Fancy" certification is not. A harvest from Koa's farm produces only a limited number of Peaberry bags per season. This scarcity, combined with the hand-sorting labor, justifies the higher price point and makes Peaberry a natural choice for gifting or for the buyer who wants to give the origin its best possible showcase.</p>

<p class="body">Koa's Peaberry has won the prestigious Gevalia Kaffe Prize at the Kona Coffee Cultural Festival multiple times and is consistently rated by specialty coffee buyers as among the best coffees produced in Hawaii. Milk chocolate, hazelnut, bright citrus: a cup that reads clean, sweet, and distinctive from the first sip. At $60 to $225 depending on quantity, it is one of the more expensive single-origin coffees available from US domestic production, and one of the few that earns the price.</p>

<h2 class="section-head">Ka'u and Waialua: <em>Hawaii Beyond Kona</em></h2>

<h3 class="sub-head">Ka'u: The Rising Region</h3>
<p class="body">Ka'u is a coffee-growing district on the southern tip of Hawaii's Big Island, separated from the Kona belt by Mauna Loa and a significantly different microclimate. Where Kona's western slope gets the morning sun and afternoon cloud pattern that defines its growing conditions, Ka'u's southern exposure produces more consistent cloud cover, heavier rainfall, and slightly different soil conditions derived from older volcanic flows.</p>

<p class="body">Ka'u coffee has built a genuine specialty reputation in the years since farms there began producing at quality levels comparable to Kona. The cup profile differs: Ka'u coffees tend toward darker fruit notes, wine-like complexity, and a slightly earthier quality compared to the clean, sweet clarity of north Kona. Ka'u won the Gevalia Kaffe Cup of Excellence competition, placing it on the international specialty coffee map alongside the world's most acclaimed origins. Buyers who have exhausted their Kona exploration and want to compare Hawaii's two primary regions will find Ka'u an interesting contrast.</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">Waialua: Oahu's Forgotten Coffee</h3>
<p class="body">Waialua Estate on the North Shore of Oahu is a former sugar plantation converted to coffee, cacao, and other specialty crops in the 1990s after sugar production became economically unviable on the island. Waialua coffee occupies a different climate and soil context than either Kona or Ka'u: it is lower elevation and warmer, growing in former cane-field soil with irrigation support rather than the reliable rainfall of the volcanic slopes.</p>

<p class="body">Waialua coffee is more limited in production and distribution than Kona or Ka'u, and its flavor profile is distinctively different: less citrus brightness, more full body, and a profile that reads closer to a Caribbean coffee than a volcanic Hawaiian one. For collectors of Hawaiian coffees or buyers who want to explore the full range of what the state produces, Waialua is a worthwhile tangent. For the buyer whose primary goal is experiencing the best Hawaiian coffee, Kona and Ka'u are the main events.</p>

<h2 class="section-head">Tasting Notes <em>by Roast Level</em></h2>

<p class="body">Kona coffee's flavor responds to roast level more dramatically than many other origins because the origin character is relatively delicate and clean rather than intensely fruit-forward or earth-driven. Understanding what each roast level does allows you to buy with your preferred cup profile in mind.</p>

<p class="body"><strong>Light roast (City):</strong> The brightest expression of Kona's citrus character: lemon curd, bergamot, stone fruit, and a lighter body that emphasizes acidity. This roast level rewards pour-over brewing and shows the origin's terroir most transparently. Less common from Kona producers, who tend toward medium for the market they serve.</p>

<p class="body"><strong>Medium roast (City+, Full City):</strong> The sweet spot for most Kona buyers. Milk chocolate, hazelnut, caramel, and a balanced brightness that is approachable but not flat. This is the roast level at which most Koa Coffee products are offered, and it represents the majority consensus on what Kona should taste like: sweet, clean, complex enough to reward attention, and easy enough to enjoy without concentration.</p>

<p class="body"><strong>Medium-dark roast (Full City+, Vienna):</strong> Deeper chocolate, more roast character, less citrus brightness. The origin's natural sweetness comes through as a bittersweet dark chocolate quality. Koa's Grande Domaine Vienna Roast is the example at this level. For buyers who enjoy bold coffee or who use milk and want the coffee's character to come through the dairy, this is the practical choice.</p>

<p class="body"><strong>Dark roast (French, Italian):</strong> At very dark roast levels, the unique Kona character is largely replaced by roast-derived flavors: charcoal, bittersweet dark chocolate, minimal acidity. This is not the recommended approach for 100% Kona if the goal is tasting what you paid for. If someone specifically wants dark-roasted coffee, commodity alternatives exist at a fraction of the price.</p>

<h2 class="section-head">Brewing Recommendations <em>for Kona</em></h2>

<p class="body">Kona's clean, balanced profile suits a wide range of brewing methods, but some bring out its character better than others.</p>

<p class="body"><strong>Pour-over (V60, Chemex, Kalita):</strong> The best method for experiencing Kona's full aromatic character. Clean filtration preserves the citrus brightness and allows the subtle milk chocolate notes to come through without muddiness. Use water at 200-205 degrees Fahrenheit (93-96 Celsius), a medium-fine grind, and a standard 1:15 to 1:16 coffee-to-water ratio.</p>

<p class="body"><strong>Drip coffee maker:</strong> Excellent for everyday Kona consumption. A quality drip brewer with a thermal carafe (not a hot plate that bakes the coffee) preserves the origin's sweetness well. Medium roast is most practical for drip.</p>

<p class="body"><strong>French press:</strong> Adds body and allows some oils through the metal filter, which can enhance the chocolate and hazelnut notes. Use a slightly coarser grind than pour-over to prevent over-extraction. The result is richer and heavier than a clean pour-over.</p>

<p class="body"><strong>Espresso:</strong> Kona makes an unusual but genuinely excellent espresso base. The natural sweetness and milk chocolate character work well under pressure, and the citrus brightness reads as a pleasant acidity in the espresso shot. Pull at standard espresso parameters (18-19g in, 36-38g out, 27-32 seconds) and expect a shot with good body and natural sweetness.</p>

